2. ACID Properties (Database Reliability) ğŸ”’
ğŸ§  Logic: ACID is an acronym defining four key properties guaranteed by a reliable database transaction system (specifically Relational Database Management Systems - RDBMS). These properties ensure that data is handled reliably and correctly, even during errors or power failures.A $\mathbf{Transaction}$ is a single logical unit of work that must either succeed completely or fail completely.ğŸ“Œ The Four ACID Properties:PropertyDefinitionAnalogyAtomicityThe transaction is treated as a $\mathbf{single,~indivisible}$ unit. It either fully commits or completely aborts (Rollback).Money transfer: either withdrawal AND deposit both happen, or neither happens.ConsistencyThe transaction moves the database from one $\mathbfvalid~state$ to another. Data integrity rules (constraints) are always maintained.A balance field must never be negative.IsolationConcurrent transactions execute $\mathbf{independently}$ and $\mathbf{without~interference}$. It's as if they run one after another.Multiple users updating the same record don't see each other's partial changes.DurabilityOnce a transaction is committed, its changes are $\mathbf{permanent}$ and survive system failures (like crashes or power loss).The committed data is saved to non-volatile storage (disk).ğŸ¤¹â€â™€ï¸ Java Code (Conceptual Transaction):Javatry (Connection conn = getConnection()) {
    conn.setAutoCommit(false); // Start transaction block

    // Atomicity: If this fails, the next step and commit won't run.
    executeWithdrawal(conn, 100); 
    
    // Consistency: Constraints ensure the state remains valid.
    executeDeposit(conn, 100); 

    conn.commit(); // Durable commit
} catch (SQLException e) {
    conn.rollback(); // Atomicity ensures state integrity
} 
// Isolation is handled automatically by the RDBMS locking mechanisms.
